{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn85038220/00340580722/1949032401/0203.xml":{"full_text":"VOLUME LXXVIIX, NO. 33\nI\n*4\n\u25a0L:\n\u2014Photo by Bmlttya studio\nRUSSELL BOERGER\nUnion County farmers .have\nbeen invited to participate in a\nUnion-Madison county beef cat\ntle tour to be held next Tuesday.\nSeveral 4-H club members with\nsteer projects arc also planning\nto go on the tour, according to\nCpunty Agent Frank Greeneisen.\nItinerary for the day is as fol\nlows:\n10 a. m.-\u2014Madison County Ex\nperiment farm, 2\u00a5i miles north\nwest of London on Fish Hatchery\nrd.\n10:45 a. m.\u2014Emerson Ernst\nfarm, west of Somerfort.\n11:15 a. m.\u2014Vivian Overtuf\nfarm, west of Somerfort.\n12 noon\u2014Lunch at Fettrow\u2019s\nrestaurant.\n1 p. m.\u2014Upper Gwynn farm,\nfirst north of Route 40 on Route\n38.\n2 p. m.\u2014William Rausch farm,\nmiles nprth of Rosedale on\nRoute 38.\n2:45 p. m.\u2014William Ryan farm,\nRoute 161 between Chuckery and\nIrwin.\n3:15 p. m.\u2014Patti Ryan farm,\nnorth of Irwin on Route 36.\n4 p. m.\u2014Harold Bishop farm,\n3 miles west of Milford Center.\nThe tour has been arranged to\ninclude both breeding and feed\ning herds, Mr. Gtecncisen sard.\nTwo Years on New Guinea\nInteresting for Boerger\n\u2018.\u2018It\u2019s sure, good to be home\nagain!\u2019*.\nThat is the sentiment of Rttssdl\nBoerger, 20, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nChris Boerger of near Marysville,\nwho got back home March 10 af\nter two years as a lay missionary\nin New Guinea.\n\u201cIt was a fine experience -und\nI am glad to have had it,\u201d the\ntanned and healthy-lboking young\nman declared, \u201cbut I am glad to\nbe back home again.\u201d\nYoung Boerger left home Sept.\n23, 1946. sailed from San Fran\ncisco Sept. 28, and arrived in\nNew Guinea Nov. 5. During the\nensuing 27 months, he had some\nmemorable experiences.\nNight with Cannibals\n\u201cThe entire adventure was\nsomething to remember,\u201d he\nsummed up, \u201cbut the thing which\nwill stay with as the most re\nmarkable experience of all was\nthe night I spent in a cannibal\nvillage.\u201d\nColeman Re-elected President As\nCounty T. B. Group Meets Saturday\nWilliam L. Coleman, Marys\nattorney, was re-elected president\nof the Union County Tubercu\nlosis and Health Association as\nthat group held its annual meet\ning Saturday afternoon in the\nhigh school building. Other of\nficers chosen were:\nH. W. Carr, vice president Mrs.\nE. J. Marsh, secretary Mrs.\nGeorge Maney, treasurer Luther\nL. Liggett, representative di\nrctor Mrs. E. B. Ingmire, alter\nnate and the executive commit\ntee, Mrs. Alvi Graham, and Mrs.\nFred Callaway, three years Mrs.\nT. A. Davin, and Ethel Anderson,\ntwo years Mrs. R. J. Langstaff\nand Mrs. H. H. Kettler, one year.\nMrs. Maney gave the annual\ntreasurer\u2019s report. A few items of\ninterest to the public, are the dis\nbursement of S341 for 97 X-Rays\nS32 for X-Ray interpretations\n$18 for 64 clinic patients, $500\nBeef Callie Tour\nSlated Tuesday\npaid to the County Health De\npartment for nursing service,\ntravel expenses, and education in\ntuberculosis work. The Execu\ntive Secretary announced re\nceipts of the 42nd Christmas\nSeal Sales were $2983.99, and the\nstate and National program,\nS594.20.\nMr. Liggett spoke to the group\nbn the representatives directors\u2019\nmeetings he had attended in Col\numbus, and the reports of the\nwork that is being accomplished.\nTownship chairman to serve for\nthe coming year are:\nAllert^ Mrs. Glen Stillings\nClaiborne, Mrs R. J. Langstaff\nDarby, Mrs. T. A. Davin, Mrs.\nClifton Holycross, Mis. E. B. In\ngmire Dover, Mrs. Paul Tossey\nJackson, Mrs. Wilbur Parish\nJerome, Mrs. Thad Seeley Lees\nburg, Mrs. J. O. Eddy Liberty,\nMrs. Thurman Skidmore, Mrs. C.\nF. Diehl Peoria, Mrs. Paul Jew\nell Paris, Mrs. Charles Mills\nTaylor, Mrs. E. J. Marsh Union,\nMrs. H. H. Kettler, Mrs. Norman\nHageman Washington, Mrs. Her\nbert Coons: York, Mrs. Charles\nSmith Millcreek, Mrs. Carl\nBlumenchein.\nMr. Coleman introduced the\nguest speaker, Mrs. Dorothy\nRoyce, county nurse supervisor.\nShe told of the acomplishmcnts\nthe Health Department had\nmade in the county this past\nyear in the tuberculosis work,\nespecially the X-Hay and Clinic\nservice at the Clark County\nSanatorium, which is being fi\nnanced by the tuberculosis as\nsociation.\nAlso the continued follow up\nwork since the Free Chest X-Ray\nservice at the county fair. The\ndoctors of the county are plan\nning to have X-Ray service a\nvailable in Richwood and Plain\nCity. The County Health De\npartment and Tuberculosis asso\nciation will soon start plans for\nthe Free Chest X-Ray Service to\nbe held again Ibis year at the\nCounty Fair.\nProgram in Raymond\nThe Crawford Brothers, radio\nentertainers on station WRFD\nwill present a comedy and mus\nical program on Friday night,\nApril 1 at the Raymond School\nAuditorium. Admission 50c.\nChurches Urge Public to Listen To\n'Que Great Hour\n\"One Great Hour\u201d, a Nation\nwide broadcast on the eve of a\nunited offering will dramatize\nthe work of churches overseas\nand urge all Americans to at\ntend church and participate in\nthe offering on Sunday morning.\nOne Great Hour is to the hour\nbetween 10 and Up. m. Satur\nday. The program of this hour\nwill be broadcast, for America\u2019s\nchurches, over nearly every ma\njor radio station in the country to\nan estimated 50,000,000 people.\nThe full networks of the Colum\nbia Broadcasting System, Ameri\ncan Broadcasting Company and\nthe Mutual Broadcasting System\nhave been qwitributed for tlys\nprogram.\nOne Great Hour, written under\nthe direction of the noted play\nwright and author, Robert Sher\nwood, and by Erik Bainouw, na\ntional president of the Radio\nWriter\u2019s Guild, will dramatize the\nSalurday Evening\nplight of the war-stricken and\nsuffering people in countries of\nEurope and Asia.. It will make\nreal their desperate need for ma\nterial aid\u2014for food, medicine and\nclothing that will give them\nstrength to build a new physical\nworld. Even more important, it\nwill make real their great hunger\nfor the Christian faith that will\ngive them strength to rebuild\ntheir spiritual world the Chris\ntian faith that can be strengthen\ned by this united action of Chris\ntian churches in America.\nThis drama will be brought to\nlife by great stars of stage, screen\nand radio who offered to contri\nbute their talents. Among them\nwill be Gregory Peck, Ida Lu\npine, and Robert Montgomery.\nThe world famous overseas co1 re\nspondent, writer and commen\ntator, Quentin Reynolds, will act\n(CuutiuueJ on Pag* Co1- Z\n,'Asf it turned out, .nothing ex\nceptional happened that night\nand the natives were very\u2019 hos*\npitable to him and his two com\npanions, but young Boerger con\nfesses to being uneasy the entire\ntime they were there.\nThis particular occasion came\nup, the young man recalls when\nhe, a missionary and another lay\nworker were on a trip into the\nmountainous inland of the island.\nIt was one of their stops on a 250\nmile journey afoot and on horse\nback to visit different stations.\nWore Human Bones\n\u201cWhen we got to the village,\nthe natives were wearing human\nbones as ornaments,\u201d Boerger re\ncalled. \u201cIt was a gruesome sight,\nand the way they eyed our trad\ning goods, like they would like to\nsteal them, didn\u2019t help.\nBut the trio were accorded fine\ntreatment at the hands of the\n(Continued on Page 3. Col. 2)\nOstrander Farmer\nWins Top Award For\nDHIA Division\nWalter Hickok, of Ostrander,\nreceived a bronze and walnut\nplaque and $45 as first prize for\nexcellence in dairying during\nceremonies, Tuesday night, as a\npart of Farmers Week at Ohio\nState University.\nHickok, winner of the Dairy\nHerd Improvement Association\ndivision, has had his herd of\nregistered Guernseys on test\nsince 1935. He began testing with\nthe Union county service unit,\nbut joined the Delaware unit at\nits inception in 1939. He operates\ntwo farms in the county, one for\nhis milk cows and one for one\nstock.\nStandards for the awarding of\nprizes to DHIA member winners\ninclude the repair and mainten-\"\nance of the contestant\u2019s build\nings and equipment, the care he\ngives his animals, his use qf con\nservation practices, his use of im\nproved breeding practices, his\nmanner of keeping records and\nhis milk handling practices.\nDriver is Unhurt\nAs Jruck Demolished\nThe driver was uninjured but\nthe tractor was almost demolished\nwhen a large semi-trailer over\nshot a curve on Route 4 about 7\nmiles north of Marysville at 3:30\np. m. Monday.\nThe truck, an International\nowned by Mack Brothers Furni\nture Co., of Berea, was driven by\nBert Scanlon who said that he\nover-shot a curve and went off\nthe road on the right side. He\nwhipped the truck back on the\nroad only to slide off the left\nside, hit a culvert, and turned\nover. Scanlon was treated by Di.\nH. E. Stricker in Marysville Xux*\ncuts and bruises and released.\nSheriff Walter Galloway in\nvestigated the accident and said\nthat he still cannot understand\nhow anyone could escape alive\nfrom the smashed truck cab.\nState D. A. V. Head\nTo be Here March 30\nUnion County Chapter No. 55\nof the Disabled American Veter\nans will meet at 8 p. m. March 30\nin the V. F. W. Hall, Marysville.\nAll veterans in Union County\nwho have a war-incurred disabili\nty are cordially invited to be\nthere.\nD. A. V. State Commander Al\nbert L. Croy, will be the speaker\nand refreshments will be served.\nCommander Croy will help veter\nans with claim problems. This\nservice is free and no employee\nor officer will accept money for\nservices.\nEvery veteran who is eligible\nshould be a member of the\nD. A. V., the organization that\nhas led the fight for America\u2019s\nsei vice-connected disabled for 25\nyears.\nPalestine Lodge Sets\nInspection March 31\nPalestine Lodge of Marysville\nwill hold its annual inspection in\nthe master mason\u2019s degree in the\nMarysville High School gym on\nMarch 31.\nLodge will open for the first\nsection at 5 p. m. followed by\ndinner at 6 p. m. in the Metho\ndist Church at $1.25 per person.\nThe second section will be con\nferred at 7:30 p. m. with Robert\nJones, D. D. G. M. of Prospect, as\nthe inspecting officer.\nTh* Union County Journal ILu By Far The Largest Circulation ol Any Paper in Union County\n\u00aeljr. Union (Pountn $onnwl\nPublished Semi-Weekly in the Best Interests ol Union County\nMARYSVILLE, OHIO MARCH 24, 1949\nBarker, Coleman\nTo Represent\nCounty Sportsmen\nConservation Group\nMeets Wednesday\nMaes Reccommendations\n-X\nJohn Barker and William L.\nColeman were elected as the\nUnion County representatives to\nthe district conservation com\nmittee during the county conser\nvation committee\u2019s meeting in the\ncommissioner\u2019s office in the\nCourt House Wednesday evening.\nMr. Barker is the farmer re\npresentative and Mr. Coleman is\nthe sportsman representative,\nfrom this county. These two men\nwill help formulate the recomen\ndations which the district com\nmittee will pass on to the State\nConservation Commission for\nconsideration 1n the forming the\nconservation laws of the state.\nThe men will carry with them\nto the district, the recomendations\nmade by the Union County com\nmittee in regard to the game\nlaws of Ohio, Wednesday.\nRecomendation Made\nThe following recomendations\nwere made in regard to the open\nseasons and bag limits on the\nvarious game:\nSquirrell season, Sept. 15-30,\nbag limit, four, same number in\nposession.\nPheasant and grouse, Nov. 15\n25, bag limit, two per day. New\nhunting hours of 10 a. m. to 5:30\np.J m. were recommended to give\nthose in school or working late\na better opportunity to hunt.\nLast year\u2019s hours were from nine\nto four.\nRabbits, Nov. 15 to Dec. 18,\nbag limit of four.\nThe following recommendations\nwere made for the fur bearers.\nFur Bearers\nRaccoon, Nov. 15 to Jan. 15,\nlimit, two per day and two in po\nscssion.\nMink and muskrat, Nov. 15 to\nJan. 15, no limit.\nOppossum, same regulation as\nniink and muskrat.\nGround hog, no closed season\nthis year. Last year the season\nw/is closed from March 1 to June\nSRun\u2019k, contimte the closed\nseason started last year.\nDeer, open season on bucks\nonly and that the bucks must\nhave not less than three inch\nspikes.\nEndorse Unification\nIn addition to these recom\nmendations, the committee en\ndorses Senate Bill 13 calling for\nunification of the various ser\nvices of the conservation de\npartment. At present there are\nseven different branches of the\nState Department\nThey also recommended an a\nmendment to the bill giving fur-\n(Continued on Pago 2, Col. 2)\nA.\nI\nA number of veterans each\nmonth run the risk of allowing\ntheir National Service Life In\nsurance to lapse because- they\ndon\u2019t take a second look before\nmailing their premium payments.\nLast month the VA District Of\nfice in Columbus, which handles\nGI insurance for veterans in Ohio,\nMichigan and Kentucky, received\napproximately 350 checks, money\norders anc|.^ postal notes that\ncould not be cashed although\nthey were intended to pay NSLI\npremiums. Many checks were\nnot signed. Others were made\npayable to various companies and\nApril 1 is Deadline\nFor AAA Sign-up\nFarmers wishing to participate\nin the 1949 Agricultural Conser\nvation program must sign a 1949\nfarm plan and request approval\nof intended practices before April\n1\nThose who 'were unable to at\ntend their local sign-up meeting\ncan execute the necessary forms\nin the County AAA office any\ntime before this deadline dale.\nFor the convenience of those\nwho are unable to come in at\nany other time the office will be\nopen on Saturday, March 26.\nEngraving Plant Installed by Journal\nMakes Possible Use of Many Pictures\nFbr the past several months, as the readers have no doubt\nnoticed, The Journal has been using a great many local news pictures\nin its columns.\nThis has been made possible by the installation, in co-operation\nwith Smitty\u2019s Studio, of a complete photo-engraving plan^for the\nmaking of our own \u201ccuts\u201d.\nIt is quite readily admitted that the quality of the engravings,\nat times, was not of the best. There has, of necessity, been a long\nperiod of experimenting with the equipment, learning to use it\nproperly, learning the various highly Uichuical operations which go\ninto making a single newspaper \"cut\u201d.\nNow however, we feel that operation of the equipment has been\nmastered sufficiently to insure good quality engravings at all times.\nTherefore, it is with considerable pride that we make a public\nannouncement concerning the installation of the engraving plant.\nOur purchase and use of this equipment brings to Marysville\nand Union County, a newspaper service generally found only in the\nlarger, metropolitan newspapers.\n,We make no claim that The Journal\u2019s engraving plant is, in\nsize, cost or scope, on a par with a big city newspaper. But we do\nwish to point out that very few small town newspapers are able to\nmake their Qwn \u201ccuts\u201d at all and installation of the equipment by\nThe Journal makes it possible to bring to its readers, pictures of\nnews events as soon as they happen, just as the city papers do.\nInstallation of the engraving plant is in keeping with The\nJournal\u2019s and Smitty\u2019s constant effort to serve Marysville and Union\nCounty another step in The Journal\u2019s constant program of provid\ning the community with the best kind ol newspaper it is possible\nto print here.\nThe Journal, and Smitty, felt Marysville and Union County is\nentitled to this type of service and so put in the necessary equipment\nat no small cost in time and money for both of us.\nWe will constantly endeavor to obtain photographs which will\nproperly illustrate the news as it occurs or help bring to the atten\ntion of the public the worthy activities of Union County\u2019s organiza\ntions.\nAt the same time, we hope the general public will remember\nthat The Journal is interested in obtaining pictures of everything\nappropriate. Nearly everything that happens is worth a picture and\nwe stand ready to lend our services toward that goal.\nJust let us know about your anniversary celebrations, individual\naccomplishments, organization activities and we\u2019ll take it from there.\nLegion Members Honored}Taesday\nThlrty-year members of Union Post No. 79. American Legion, were honored by the post at a\nspecial meeting. Tuesday evening. Among the World War 1 veterans present for the occasion were\nthese charter members of the local post. From left to right:\nStanding\u2014Albert Fensel. Martin Fensel, Louis P. Rausch. McKinley Haines, and Wilbur Forry.\nSeated\u2014Fay .Turner, first adjutant of the post, and iDf. F. Q. Callaway, earlist commander\npresent.\nMany Veterans Careless About Checks\nFor Insurance, Run Risk oh Lasing It\norganizations that have no con\nnection with the Veterans Ad\nministration.\nOne veteran, for example, sent\nVA a check obviously intended\nfor his local telephone company\nand, apparently, the telephone\ncompany received the check he\nhad intended to send to the Vet\nerans Administration. This it\u00bb a\nfairly common error.\nVA attempts to clear up such\nmistakes umnediately, but if the\nDairymen Seek\nTo Halt Recession\nAn aroused dairy industry set\nin motion a new business action\nprogram of advertising, mer\nchandising and research to\nblock creeping recession in the\nmarkets for dairy foods, Earl B.\nPoling, Marysville, Ohio execu\ntive secretary of the American\nDairy Association, reported to\nday on his return from the na\ntionwide dairy rally in Chicago.\nin highlighting the business\nblueprint, Mr. Poling pointed out\nthat June Dairy Month has been\ndesignated action time by the\nnation\u2019s 5 million dairy farmers.\nThe 30-day period, he added,will\nbe fund-raising time for the\nfarmers to finance a year\u2019s cam\npaign.\nDelegates from 40 states, re\npresenting 90 percent of the na\ntion\u2019s milk production, mapped\nout newspaper, magazine and out\ndoor advertising pointing to\ngreater use of dairy foods and\nbetter public understanding of\nthe importance of the dairy in\ndustry to economy.\nAt the three-day session, spon\nsored by the American Dairy As\nsociation, Mr. Poling asserted,\nfarmers agreed with housewives\nof the nation on removal of oleo\nmargarine taxes and safeguard\ning butter\u2019s natural yellow color\nagainst imitation.\nSales Tax Collections\nShow Slight Gain\nSales tax collections in Union\nCounty for the week ending\nMarch 5 were $3,800.38 accoi ding\nto a report from State Treasurer\nDon Ebright. This was slightly\nahead of the S3.687.11 for the\nsame period of 194-3. Tax collec\ntion to date for 1949 in Union\nCounty total $28,034.97 which is\nbehind last year\u2019s total.\nCollections in the neighboring\ncounty\u2019s arc as follows: Cham\npaign, S4.370.81 Delaware, S4,\n378.85 Franklin, $179,653.66 Har\ndin, $4,609.04 Logan, $7,358.82\nMadison, $3,449.65 Marion, $12,\n250.98.\nBox Social Cancelled\nBox social and cake walk\nscheduled for March 25, in the\nYork Local School, sponsored by\nthe P. T. A., has been cancelled\nuntil further notice.\nQuartet at Claiborne\nThe Aurora College male quar\ntet will sing at the Claiborne Ad\nvent Church, March 25. There is\nno charge and everybody is wel\ncome.\n\u2022V\nN A\nUiH x-WK\nssj-y 'At\n\u2018I\nA\na FB\nV\nf.\n'X\nirrAt\nveteran who forgets to sign his\ncheck, or mails the wrong one,\nis near the end of his 31-day\ngrace period there is alway^i the\ndanger that his insurance may\nlapse.\nWhen improperly executed\npayments are received, VA writes\nto the veteran within 24 hours.\nBut his premium cannot be mark\ned \u201cpaid\" until he sends back a\ncashable payment.\nFailure to use the premium\npayment envelope provided by\nVA also slows up the process of\ncrediting payments for some\nveterans. All necessary informa\ntion, including the veteran\u2019s in\nsurance number, is printed on the\npremium payment envelopes\nsent regularly to veterans who\nhave kept their insurance in\nforce. Regular usa of these spec\nial envelopes makes it more con\nvenient for the veteran to make\nhis premium payments find in\nsures faster and more accurate\nservice by VA.\nVA insurance officials point\nout that all checks, money orders\nor postal notes should be made\npayable to the Treasurer of the\nUnited States. If for any reason\nthe veteran docs not have a pre\nmium envelope and does not\nknow his insurance number, he\nshould make sure, his payment\nis accompanied by his full name,\naddress and armed forces serial\nnumber.\nRules for Sales Tax on\nFeed, Seeds, Plants\nThere exists uncertainty in\nsome sections of the state as to\nthe proper application of the\nsales tax on sales of feed, seeds\nand plants.\nSales of feed, including pet\nfood, arc not taxable. Sales of\nvegetable, flower an grass seeds\nare not subject to the application\nof the tax.\nSales of food producing plants\nsuch as vegetable and fruit plants\nare not subject to the applica\ntion of the tax, Tfois exemption\nalso applies to sales of fruit trees.\nJournal Printing\nIs Always\nPino Printing\nPrice Per Copy Five Centt\nRelief Load Up\nNine Cases Over\nJanuary Total\nBut February Cost\nIs Less Due To Fewer\nDoctor, Hospital Bills\nThere were nine more cases on\nrelief last month than during Jan\nuary although the financial load\nwas $350 less, according to fig\nures released by Mrs. Katherine\nDennis, head of the division of\npublic assistance.\n\u201cThe reason for this\", Mrs. Den\nnis explained,\u201cjs that the Jan\nuary checks included many\nlargo doctor and hospital bills\nwhile the bulk of the February\npayments were small checks for\nthose who are out of work due to\nsome temporary lay-off.\u201d\nTh\u00ae total payments for Feb\nruary were $1859.03 as compared\nwith $2207.25 for the month be\nfore.\nThe 60 cases inrfttdrd 123\npeople as compared with 118\npeople involved in the 51 cases in\nJanuary.\nAlthough the office had the\nsame number of cases (60) in\nFebruary, 1948, the total pay\nments were much higher. Relief\nchecks for that month amounted\nto $2154.97.\n\u201cThis can partly be explained\nby the fact that a year ago al\nmost 80 more people were con\nnected with the same number of\ncases,\u201d Mrs. Dennis pointed out.\n\u2014\u2014^1 I\nBbhop io Head\nCo-op Diieciors\nRowland Bishop, Union Town\nship, was elected chairman of the\nBoard of Directors of the Union\nCounty Farm Bureau Cooperat\nive Association at their reorgani\nzation meeting on Monday. Other\nofficers named were Robert\nMather, Claiborne Township, vice\nchairman, and Joseph Easton,\nDover Township, secretary-treas\nurer.\nMembers of the board are Fred\n\u25a0Reeiey, Jackson Township Lewis\nNicol, Paris Township Chris\nBoerger, Paris Township Guy\nGreen, York Township Herbert\nCoons, Washington Township Lee\nDeVitt, Paris Township: Robert\nMather, Claiborne Township Paul\nDavis, Jerome Township Harold\nBishop, Allen Township Joseph\nEaston, Dover Township, and\nRowland Bishop, Union Town*\nship.\nCommittees appointed by\nChairman Bishop are:\nExecutive o i 11 e e\u2014Mr.\nBishop, Robert Mather. Joseph\nEaston, DeViU and Harold\nBishop.\nFinance Committe\u2014Guy Green\nchairman, Paul Davis, Lewis\nNicol and Randall Spencer.\nInventory committee\u2014C I s\nBoerger, chairman, Herbert\nCoons and Robert Mathehr.\nPublic Relations committee\u2014\nMr. Bishop, chairman, Robert\nMather and Les Cullman.\nPersonal committee\u2014Le DeVitt,\nchairman, Joe Easton and Mer\nritt Sharf\nOrgan at Pharisburg\nA Hammond electric organ will\nbe placed in the Pharisburg\nMethodist Church for use this\nSunday. It will be played dur\ning the worship hour, for the ser\nvice, by a representative of the\ncompany. All are invited to wor\nship with us. and to enjoy the\nmusic of the Hammond organ.\nHigh School Seniors 'Run County\nOu 'Goveinuieul Du/ Sei April 11\nSeniors from 10 Union County\nHigh Schools will take over the\nvarious county offices for the\nday on April 11 according to\nGale W. Baldwin, county super\nintendant of schools.\nThis will be the second annual\n\u201cCounty Government Day for\nUnion County High Schools and\nis intended to give the seniors of\nthe high schools a clearer picture\nof the functions of county gov\nernment.\nEach school will select two to\nfour seniors, depending on the\nsize of the enrollment, to fill the\noffices assigned to them by the\ncounty office. The method of se\nlection wiU be leU up U the kcal\nfaculties.\nThose picked to participate in\nthe government day will meet at\nthe county superintendent\u2019s of\nfice at 9 a. m. to receive their in\nstructions and a briefing of the\nday\u2019s activities.\nFollowing is a list of the county\noffices and the schools assigned\nto fill them:\nAuditor. Union and Magnetic.\nProsecuting Attorney, York.\nHealth Department, Richwood\nand Jerome.\nSanitarian. Liberty.\nSheriff. Taylor and Millcreek.\nCommissioners, W a s i n gton,\nUnion, and Darby.\nRecorder, Darby and Jeiome.\nClerk ol Courts, Liberty and\nYork.\nTreasurer. Union and Washing\nton.\nProbate Judge, Richwood'tnd\nDarby\nCounty SupL* Jeiome and\nTaylor.\nEngineer, Millcreek and Rich\nwood.\nRcprrsmtnHve, M\u2019agnetft\nCommon Pleas Judge, Liberty\nWelfare Dept., Richwood and\nMagnetic.","height":"27186","width":"21735"}}
